The Severing: 1971--1980 {#the-severing-19711980 .font-display .text-2xl .font-semibold .text-white .tracking-wide .uppercase}
::::
:::::::::::::::::::::: {.bg-card .rounded-xl .p-8 .border .border-white/5 .space-y-6} When the gold standard broke, it wasn\'t merely a monetary shift. It was a **reality constraint removal**.
For the first time in American history, the government could create wealth *symbolically* instead of *productively*.
The Federal Reserve immediately began what it called \"monetary accommodation.\" The rest of us call it: printing money to sustain spending beyond production.
:::: {.data-callout .rounded-xl .p-6} ::: {.font-sans .text-xs .uppercase .tracking-widest .text-amber/70 .mb-4 .font-semibold} The Mechanism :::
1. [1.]{.font-mono .text-accent .font-bold .flex-shrink-0} Government wants to spend more than tax revenue allows 2. [2.]{.font-mono .text-accent .font-bold .flex-shrink-0} Instead of raising taxes, it borrows from the Fed 3. [3.]{.font-mono .text-accent .font-bold .flex-shrink-0} Fed creates new money (from nothing) to buy government bonds 4. [4.]{.font-mono .text-accent .font-bold .flex-shrink-0} That new money flows into the economy 5. [5.]{.font-mono .text-accent .font-bold .flex-shrink-0} Prices rise (inflation), but wages lag behind 6. [6.]{.font-mono .text-accent .font-bold .flex-shrink-0} Net result: real wealth transfers from wage-earners to asset-holders and government ::::
::: {.pullquote .pl-6 .py-4 .rounded-r-lg} This isn\'t capitalism. It isn\'t socialism. It\'s **extraction through monetary deception**. :::

